2026-03-08T01:03:16.713827Z  INFO session_loop{thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b}:submission_dispatch{submission.id="019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad"}:turn{otel.name="session_task.turn" thread.id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b turn.id=019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad model=gpt-5.4}: codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: exec_command {"cmd":"printf '===== STRICT BOUNDARIES =====\\n'; nl -ba .codex/policies/strict-boundaries.md | sed -n '1,220p'; printf '\\n===== SECURITY DOC =====\\n'; nl -ba docs/security-publishing.md | sed -n '1,220p'; printf '\\n===== CONFIG =====\\n'; nl -ba .codex/config.toml | sed -n '1,120p'; printf '\\n===== PARALLEL ORCH =====\\n'; nl -ba .codex/knowledge/parallel-orchestration/SKILL.md | sed -n '1,220p'; printf '\\n===== SDD =====\\n'; nl -ba .codex/knowledge/subagent-driven-development/SKILL.md | sed -n '1,220p'","workdir":"/Users/lewis/1-Backup/0-devback/archive/codex_ai-agentic-sdd","yield_time_ms":1000,"max_output_tokens":9000} thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b
2026-03-08T01:04:35.721781Z  INFO session_loop{thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b}:submission_dispatch{submission.id="019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad"}:turn{otel.name="session_task.turn" thread.id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b turn.id=019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad model=gpt-5.4}: codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: exec_command {"cmd":"cat > \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/investigation.md\" <<'EOF'\n# Investigation: Codex Flow Audit\n\n## Summary\n> This analysis evaluates whether the current `.codex` orchestration flow is genuinely optimized for Codex and competitive with the current state of AI coding agents. The repository is not an application codebase; it is an orchestration template made of prompts, roles, policies, and knowledge files. The core question is not whether the prompts are well written in isolation, but whether the full operating model is internally consistent, enforceable, low-friction for Codex, and aligned with current market capabilities such as isolated execution, parallel agents, review loops, and policy automation.\n\n## Current State\n- **Tech Stack**: Markdown-first orchestration repository for Codex; local Codex runtime config in `.codex/config.toml`; no app runtime like Node, Java, or Docker detected in this repo.\n- **Relevant Code**: `.codex/MANUAL.md`, `.codex/prompts/*.md`, `.codex/policies/*.md`, `.codex/roles/*.md`, `.codex/knowledge/*.md`, `docs/00-general-docs.md`, `docs/security-publishing.md`, `.gitignore`.\n- **Architecture**: Prompt-driven, docs-first, role-based orchestration with four explicit phases (`think` -> `forge` -> `test` -> `ship`) and plan artifacts written to `.orchestrator/plans/`.\n\n## Requirements\n### Functional\n- [x] Assess the actual `.codex` workflow as implemented, not as intended.\n- [x] Determine whether the flow is optimized for Codex specifically.\n- [x] Compare the design against current market patterns for AI coding agents.\n- [x] Identify reusable strengths, bottlenecks, contradictions, and missing enforcement.\n- [x] Produce a theoretical improvement plan without modifying source files.\n\n### Non-Functional\n- Performance: Keep prompt/context overhead low; avoid loading irrelevant docs; reduce duplication between prompts and policies.\n- Security: Prevent credential leakage, unsafe auto-execution, and policy bypass; avoid storing sensitive runtime state in publishable repos.\n\n## Scope\n### In Scope\n- Prompt architecture and phase model.\n- Role design and domain boundaries.\n- Documentation strategy and source-of-truth assumptions.\n- Operational safety, git workflow, and security posture.\n- Fitness for Codex's current local/cloud agent model.\n- Gaps relative to current agent products and workflows.\n\n### Out of Scope\n- Implementing any prompt, policy, or config changes.\n- Benchmarking token cost, latency, or success rate with live agent runs.\n- Verifying unpublished private product capabilities beyond official public docs.\n\n## Deep Analysis\n\n### 1. What is being requested?\nThe user is asking whether this `.codex` operating system is already best-in-class for Codex and, more broadly, whether it matches the strongest currently available AI agent workflows. This is an architectural audit of the orchestration layer itself.\n\n### 2. Why is it needed?\nA prompt stack can look sophisticated while still underperforming in practice because of context bloat, contradictory instructions, weak enforcement, or missing runtime primitives. If the workflow is intended to be a durable engineering operating system, these issues directly affect reliability, cost, safety, and developer trust.\n\n### 3. Where does it fit?\nIt primarily affects the orchestrator layer:\n- `docs/` as declared source of truth.\n- `.codex/prompts/` as task lifecycle interface.\n- `.codex/policies/` as governance.\n- `.codex/roles/` and `.codex/knowledge/` as specialization and reusable heuristics.\n- `.orchestrator/plans/` as execution memory.\n- `.codex/config.toml` as the only visible runtime configuration.\n\n### 4. What exists that can be reused or extended?\nStrong foundations already exist:\n- A clear phase split between planning and implementation in `.codex/prompts/think.md` and `.codex/prompts/forge.md`.\n- Explicit atomic-task philosophy in `.codex/MANUAL.md` and `.codex/knowledge/subagent-driven-development/SKILL.md`.\n- Security publication guidance in `docs/security-publishing.md`.\n- Useful separation of concerns between manual, policies, roles, and knowledge.\n- Resume/checkpoint behavior via `status.md`.\n\n### 5. What are the risks and edge cases?\n- The docs-first contract is fragile because the docs corpus is currently too thin for the rules it claims to enforce.\n- Several instructions are policy, not enforcement; runtime compliance depends on agent obedience.\n- Some files are tuned for Claude Code concepts rather than Codex-native mechanics.\n- The system claims genericity but embeds stack-specific assumptions (Spring Boot, React, Tailwind) in core roles and skills.\n- Security documentation references scripts and CI assets that do not exist in this repository.\n- The repository contains local `.codex` runtime artifacts, which is risky for a reusable template.\n\n## Findings\n\n### Strengths\n- **Good separation of concerns**: manual, prompts, roles, policies, and skills are split cleanly.\n- **Read-only planning phase is well defined**: `think` mirrors `forge` without implementation, which is good operational design.\n- **Atomic task philosophy is correct**: 5-15 minute tasks match what autonomous coding agents handle best.\n- **Status/resume artifacts are practical**: the plan folder structure is simple and robust.\n- **Docs-first discipline is directionally right**: forcing an index-first read path reduces blind context loading.\n\n### Gaps and Limitations\n- **Not fully optimized for Codex specifically**: the flow is prompt-centric, not Codex-runtime-centric. It lacks native enforcement hooks, environment bootstrapping, background task strategy, or model routing tailored to Codex.\n- **Not best-in-market today**: current leading agent workflows emphasize isolated sandboxes, background agents, persistent session controls, environment manifests, and stronger policy automation. This repo mostly documents those ideas rather than operationalizing them.\n- **Instruction drift and duplication**: the same concepts appear in the manual, policies, prompts, roles, and skills, increasing maintenance cost and the chance of conflict.\n- **Generic on paper, opinionated in practice**: several roles and skills assume Java/Spring or React/Tailwind even though the repo presents itself as generic.\n- **Missing hard guardrails**: there are no visible hook files, CI workflows, validation scripts, or pre-flight automation backing many of the rules.\n\n## Evidence from the Codebase\n- `.codex/MANUAL.md:41` makes `docs/` the supreme authority, but `docs/00-general-docs.md` only indexes one security document, leaving the rest of the documented workflow under-specified.\n- `.codex/policies/global.md:36` requires `docs/tech-stack.md`, but that file does not exist in this repo.\n- `docs/security-publishing.md:10` and `docs/security-publishing.md:24` reference `./scripts/repo-audit.sh` and `./scripts/prepublish-check.sh`, but no `scripts/` directory exists.\n- `.codex/knowledge/parallel-orchestration/SKILL.md:10` explicitly says it coordinates roles through Claude Code's agent system, which is misaligned with a Codex-branded orchestration repository.\n- `.codex/policies/strict-boundaries.md:11` through `:21` hard-code backend/frontend domain assumptions that are not generic.\n- `.codex/config.toml:1` and `:2` show one static model and `medium` reasoning effort, with no phase-specific routing.\n\n## Market Comparison (current public product direction)\nThis section is an inference from official product documentation, not a claim of identical feature parity.\n\n- **OpenAI Codex**: official Help Center documentation describes local use plus cloud delegation, isolated sandboxes per task, automated PR review, multiple agents in parallel, worktree support, skills, automations, and git functionality. The current repo mirrors planning discipline, but not the stronger operational layer.\n- **Cursor Background Agents**: official docs describe asynchronous remote agents, isolated Ubuntu environments, internet/package access, environment manifests, and branch-based handoff. This repo has no comparable environment spec or remote execution contract.\n- **GitHub Copilot coding agent**: official docs emphasize background task execution, PR creation, tracking sessions/logs, repository-level management, and external tool integrations. This repo does not expose session telemetry or reviewable agent logs beyond markdown artifacts.\n- **Claude Code**: official docs describe custom slash commands, subagents, memory files, and especially hooks that can enforce behavior around tool use. This repo uses a similar command/role philosophy but does not implement equivalent runtime hooks for Codex.\n- **Aider**: official docs highlight whole-repo mapping, fast terminal iteration, and git-centered workflows. This repo is stronger on process structure than Aider, but weaker on runtime efficiency and minimalism.\n\n## Risks\n| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|--------|------------|\n| Docs are too sparse for docs-first governance | High | Create a minimal but complete docs contract: tech stack, architecture, commands, boundaries, publishing/security |\n| Policy is not enforced by runtime hooks or CI | High | Add executable guardrails: preflight scripts, lint/check commands, and hook-based validation |\n| Claude-specific patterns leak into Codex workflow | High | Refactor the system to Codex-native terminology and capabilities |\n| Prompt duplication causes contradiction drift | Medium | Centralize invariants; let prompts reference policies instead of restating them |\n| Static model config underuses phase-specific optimization | Medium | Route planning, implementation, review, and audit to different model/reasoning profiles |\n| Shipping local `.codex` runtime artifacts | High | Separate template assets from local runtime state and harden publication checks |\n\n## Recommendation\n> The current `.codex` flow is well above average as a documentation-led prompt framework, but it is not maximally optimized for Codex and it is not at the current market frontier for AI coding agents. The biggest issue is not prompt quality; it is the gap between declared process and enforced runtime behavior. The best next move is to keep the existing phase model, atomic planning, and docs-first discipline, but rebuild the operational layer around Codex-native execution, hard guardrails, slimmer prompts, environment contracts, and measurable verification.\nEOF\nperl -0pi -e 's/\\| Investigation  \\| pending \\|/| Investigation  | done    |/' \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"\ncat \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"","workdir":"/Users/lewis/1-Backup/0-devback/archive/codex_ai-agentic-sdd","yield_time_ms":1000,"max_output_tokens":6000} thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b
2026-03-08T01:05:10.976095Z  INFO session_loop{thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b}:submission_dispatch{submission.id="019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad"}:turn{otel.name="session_task.turn" thread.id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b turn.id=019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad model=gpt-5.4}: codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: exec_command {"cmd":"cat > \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/design.md\" <<'EOF'\n# Design: Codex-Native Orchestration Hardening\n\n## Architecture Overview\n> The recommended target architecture keeps the current four-phase lifecycle because it is understandable and already encoded in the repository. The change is to make the system less prompt-heavy and more runtime-enforced. In practice, the repository should evolve from a markdown-defined orchestration framework into a Codex-native operating model with five layers: `docs/` for explicit project facts, `.codex/policies/` for stable invariants, `.codex/prompts/` for lightweight phase entrypoints, `.codex/knowledge/` for reusable heuristics, and executable guardrails (hooks/scripts/CI) for actual enforcement. This preserves the strengths of the current system while closing the gap between policy and behavior.\n\n## Operating Model\n| Layer | Current Role | Target Role |\n|------|--------------|-------------|\n| `docs/` | Declared source of truth | Minimal, complete, indexed contract for stack, architecture, commands, security, and release rules |\n| `.codex/policies/` | Human-readable rules | Canonical invariants referenced by prompts and enforced by checks/hooks |\n| `.codex/prompts/` | Large self-contained workflows | Thin phase entrypoints that import policy assumptions instead of duplicating them |\n| `.codex/knowledge/` | Skills and heuristics | Curated, versioned knowledge with explicit scope and expiry/review rules |\n| Runtime enforcement | Mostly absent | Codex-compatible validation commands, CI checks, and preflight guards |\n\n## Data Model (if applicable)\n| Entity | Key Fields | Relationships |\n|--------|-----------|---------------|\n| Plan Workspace | `slug`, `created_at`, `status`, `phase_files` | Contains `status.md`, `investigation.md`, `design.md`, `plan.md`, optionally `implementation.md` |\n| Policy Rule | `id`, `scope`, `severity`, `source_file` | Referenced by prompts and verified by checks |\n| Prompt Entry | `name`, `phase`, `required_inputs`, `outputs` | Uses policy rules and knowledge files |\n| Knowledge Item | `name`, `intent`, `applicability`, `review_cycle` | Consumed by prompts and roles |\n| Verification Check | `name`, `command`, `trigger`, `blocking` | Enforces policy and release constraints |\n\n## API Contracts (if applicable)\n| Method | Path | Body | Response | Auth |\n|--------|------|------|----------|------|\n| N/A | N/A | N/A | N/A | N/A |\n\n## Component Design (if frontend)\nNot applicable. This repository does not contain a frontend application.\n\n## File Structure\n```text\n.codex/\n├── MANUAL.md                   # Short operator manual, not policy duplicate\n├── config.toml                 # Runtime defaults and phase/model routing\n├── prompts/\n│   ├── think.md                # Thin read-only planning entrypoint\n│   ├── forge.md                # Thin implementation entrypoint\n│   ├── audit.md                # Thin audit entrypoint\n│   ├── test.md                 # Thin testing entrypoint\n│   └── ship.md                 # Delivery entrypoint with manual confirmation\n├── policies/\n│   ├── global.md               # Stable invariants only\n│   ├── strict-boundaries.md    # Role boundaries, generalized by stack profile\n│   └── secure-delivery.md      # Security/release rules\n├── knowledge/\n│   ├── software-architecture/\n│   ├── subagent-driven-development/\n│   ├── parallel-orchestration/\n│   └── ...\n├── hooks/                      # New: executable validation hooks\n└── templates/                  # New: reusable status/investigation/design/plan templates\n\ndocs/\n├── 00-general-docs.md\n├── tech-stack.md               # New required contract\n├── architecture.md             # New required contract\n├── commands.md                 # New required contract\n└── security-publishing.md\n\nscripts/\n├── repo-audit.sh               # New referenced validator\n├── prepublish-check.sh         # New referenced validator\n└── validate-plan.sh            # New plan quality gate\n```\n\n## Dependencies\n- Suggested new packages: none required at design level. Prefer shell scripts and CI-native checks first.\n- Existing packages to use: none detected in this repository.\n- External platform capabilities to leverage: Codex native plan tracking, worktree/task isolation where available, repository checks, and environment manifests.\n\n## Design Decisions\n\n### 1. Keep the phase model, shrink the prompt surface\nThe current phase split is good. The problem is duplication. Each prompt should become a thin controller for a phase, while the stable rules live in one place.\n\n### 2. Convert policies from narrative to enforceable checks\nRules like docs-first, no auto-commit, plan completeness, and secret hygiene should be backed by commands or CI. A policy without a check is advisory.\n\n### 3. Generalize stack assumptions\nThe current system claims to be generic but embeds Spring/React assumptions. The target design should either:\n- declare itself as a web full-stack template, or\n- introduce stack profiles so rules are loaded conditionally.\n\n### 4. Make Codex the primary runtime target\nAny references to Claude-specific orchestration semantics should be removed or isolated. The target design should speak in Codex-native concepts: plan files, tasks, worktrees/environments where available, explicit verification commands, and repo-local automation.\n\n### 5. Separate template assets from local runtime state\nA reusable orchestration repository should not include live local state like auth files, histories, sessions, or sqlite state. The target architecture should treat those as machine-local runtime artifacts only.\n\n### 6. Add measurable quality gates\nA modern agent workflow needs at least:\n- plan completeness check\n- docs/index consistency check\n- publishability/secret scan\n- command existence validation\n- optional benchmark log for task latency/success/cost\n\n## Modularity Check\nThis repo is not React-based. The equivalent modularity requirement here is:\n- policies define invariants\n- prompts orchestrate phases\n- knowledge files provide heuristics\n- scripts/hooks enforce rules\n- docs define project-specific facts\nNo layer should duplicate another.\n\n## Testing Strategy\n- Unit: validate shell/script checks against fixture repos or fixture plan folders.\n- Integration: run end-to-end dry runs for `think`, `forge`, `audit`, and `ship` against a sample repository.\n- Compliance: verify every documented command/path exists and every mandatory doc referenced by policy is present.\n- Security: verify denylist coverage for `.codex` runtime state and `.orchestrator` artifacts.\n\n## Target Outcome\n> After refactoring, the repository should behave like a lean orchestration kernel for Codex: small prompts, explicit docs contracts, generalized policies, actual validation hooks, and a reproducible execution model. That would move it from a strong prompt framework to a robust agent operating system.\nEOF\nperl -0pi -e 's/\\| Design         \\| pending \\|/| Design         | done    |/' \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"\ncat \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"","workdir":"/Users/lewis/1-Backup/0-devback/archive/codex_ai-agentic-sdd","yield_time_ms":1000,"max_output_tokens":5000} thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b
2026-03-08T01:05:43.185676Z  INFO session_loop{thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b}:submission_dispatch{submission.id="019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad"}:turn{otel.name="session_task.turn" thread.id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b turn.id=019ccaf7-0da2-73a1-b1de-073d3b7022ad model=gpt-5.4}: codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: exec_command {"cmd":"cat > \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/plan.md\" <<'EOF'\n# Plan: Codex Flow Audit\n\n> WARNING: This plan is strictly theoretical. No source code files have been modified.\n\n> Goal: Harden the `.codex` workflow so it is Codex-native, internally consistent, enforceable, and closer to current best-in-class AI agent operating models.\n> Architecture: Docs contract + canonical policies + thin prompts + curated knowledge + executable guardrails.\n\n## Foundation\n\n- [ ] **Task 1: Define the minimum docs contract** — `docs/00-general-docs.md`, `docs/tech-stack.md`, `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/commands.md`\n  - What: Expand the docs index and create the minimum required documents that the policies already assume exist.\n  - Verify: `docs/00-general-docs.md` links to the new files and each file exists with a non-placeholder summary.\n  - Estimate: 10 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 2: Remove policy/doc contradictions** — `.codex/MANUAL.md`, `.codex/policies/global.md`, `.codex/prompts/forge.md`, `.codex/prompts/ship.md`, `.codex/prompts/pr.md`\n  - What: Normalize the rules around branching, commit permissions, shipping, and source-of-truth responsibilities so the same rule is not stated differently in multiple places.\n  - Verify: A grep for `git commit`, `git push`, `docs/tech-stack.md`, and `Source of Truth` shows one canonical policy path and no conflicting wording.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 3: Re-scope the template as generic or stack-profiled** — `.codex/roles/*.md`, `.codex/policies/strict-boundaries.md`, relevant `.codex/knowledge/*/SKILL.md`\n  - What: Either declare the template as opinionated for React/Spring projects or add stack profiles so generic repos do not inherit irrelevant backend/frontend assumptions.\n  - Verify: Reading role docs no longer implies unsupported stacks by default.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 4: Make prompts thin and policy-referential** — `.codex/prompts/think.md`, `.codex/prompts/forge.md`, `.codex/prompts/audit.md`, `.codex/prompts/test.md`\n  - What: Reduce duplicated instructions inside prompts and reference canonical policy/knowledge files instead.\n  - Verify: Prompt files become materially shorter while preserving phase outputs and checkpoints.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n## Core\n\n- [ ] **Task 5: Replace non-Codex-specific orchestration language** — `.codex/knowledge/parallel-orchestration/SKILL.md`, `.codex/MANUAL.md`, `.codex/prompts/*.md`\n  - What: Remove Claude-specific runtime assumptions and rewrite orchestration guidance in Codex-compatible terms.\n  - Verify: `rg -n \"Claude Code|Claude\" .codex` returns no orchestration-critical references, or only clearly marked compatibility notes.\n  - Estimate: 10 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 6: Add executable repo validation scripts** — `scripts/repo-audit.sh`, `scripts/prepublish-check.sh`, optional `scripts/validate-plan.sh`\n  - What: Implement the commands already referenced by docs and add checks for missing docs, sensitive files, and referenced command existence.\n  - Verify: Running each script exits successfully on a clean repo and fails meaningfully when a required file is removed.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 7: Add runtime enforcement hooks or equivalent checks** — `.codex/hooks/*` or repo-local hook runner config, plus docs updates\n  - What: Enforce docs-first, denylisted artifact protection, and pre-ship validations through executable hooks rather than prompt text alone.\n  - Verify: A dry run blocks a forbidden action or surfaces a failing validation before execution continues.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 8: Separate publishable template from local runtime state** — `.gitignore`, repository layout docs, optional cleanup scripts\n  - What: Ensure `.codex/auth.json`, sessions, sqlite state, shell snapshots, and plan artifacts are treated strictly as local runtime data and excluded from template distribution.\n  - Verify: `git status --ignored` shows the sensitive runtime artifacts ignored and docs explain the boundary.\n  - Estimate: 10 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 9: Introduce phase-aware model/runtime guidance** — `.codex/config.toml`, `.codex/MANUAL.md`, `docs/commands.md`\n  - What: Document or configure which reasoning/runtime profile to use for planning, implementation, audit, and shipping instead of one static default.\n  - Verify: The manual and config clearly describe when to use each profile and why.\n  - Estimate: 10 min\n\n## Integration & Polish\n\n- [ ] **Task 10: Add benchmark and observability conventions** — `docs/commands.md`, `.codex/MANUAL.md`, optional `.orchestrator/templates/implementation.md`\n  - What: Define how to record task success, retries, latency, and failure modes so the workflow can be improved empirically.\n  - Verify: A sample run can capture retry count, verify command, and final outcome in a consistent format.\n  - Estimate: 10 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 11: Add a sample fixture repo for end-to-end dry runs** — `fixtures/sample-*`, `README.md` or dedicated docs\n  - What: Create a minimal sample project used to test `think`, `forge`, `audit`, and `ship` without relying on a live production repo.\n  - Verify: The orchestrator can complete a dry-run lifecycle against the fixture and produce plan artifacts without missing-doc failures.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n- [ ] **Task 12: Add CI checks for publication and contract drift** — `.github/workflows/*`, docs references\n  - What: Enforce secret scanning, required docs presence, and referenced-script existence in CI so repository health does not depend on local discipline.\n  - Verify: CI fails when required docs/scripts are removed or denylisted files become tracked.\n  - Estimate: 15 min\n\n## Validation before implementation\n- [x] Every task has What + Verify.\n- [x] Tasks are in dependency order.\n- [x] No task exceeds ~15 min.\nEOF\nperl -0pi -e 's/\\| Plan           \\| pending \\|/| Plan           | done    |/' \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"\ncat \".orchestrator/plans/2026-03-08-02-02-think-codex-flow-audit/Analiza el flujo del .codex y dime si esta opimizado al maximo para codex y de la mejor forma que hay actualmente existente en el mercado de los agentes de ia/status.md\"","workdir":"/Users/lewis/1-Backup/0-devback/archive/codex_ai-agentic-sdd","yield_time_ms":1000,"max_output_tokens":5000} thread_id=019ccaf6-2bf0-7691-a2ef-34dbb14d060b
